/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Confédération Paysanne, one of France's largest farmers' unions, has successfully fought against genetically modified organisms (GMOs), but unlike other allied movements, theirs has been led by producers rather than consumers. In Food, Farms, and Solidarity, Chaia Heller analyzes the group's complex strategies and campaigns, including a call for a Europe-wide ban on GM crops and hormone-treated beef, and a protest staged at a McDonald's. Her study of the Confédération Paysanne shows the challenges small farms face in a postindustrial agricultural world. Heller also reveals how the language the union uses to argue against GMOs encompasses more than the risks they pose; emphasizing solidarity has allowed farmers to focus on food as a cultural practice and align themselves with other workers. Heller's examination of the Confédération Paysanne's commitment to a vision of alter-globalization, the idea of substantive alternatives to neoliberal globalization, demonstrates how ecological and social justice can be restored in the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAgriculture and statezFrance. 0aAnti-globalization movementzFrance. 0aFarmersxPolitical activityzFrancexHistoryy20th century. 0aGenetically modified foodsxPolitical aspectszFrance. 0aSustainable agriculturezFrance. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822394808zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822394808423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822394808/original  a978-3-11-071183-7  Duke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013 